There are 40 different categories of specialties in the data set. These categories are related in that they are different medical specialties in the medical field. Some medical specialties focuses on the same biological system or organ in the body. None of the categories are overlapping. The most cases in the data set come from surgery followed by consult and cardiovascular/pulmonary.

Question 2

mtsamples2 <- mtsamples

library(forcats)

mtsamples2 %>%
  unnest_tokens(token, transcription) %>%
  count(token) %>%
  top_n(20, n) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, fct_reorder(token, n))) +
  geom_col()

The top words include “the”, “and”, “patient”, “she”, “he”, and other words. It is expected that these words are in the top 20 most frequent words in the transcription. Most of these words are preposition words that describes relationships between words which is required in most sentences. “Patient” is also expected to be seen a lot in the transcriptions because the physicians should be referring to the patient in their transcriptions.

Question 3

mtsamples2 %>%
  unnest_tokens(token, transcription) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = c("token" = "word")) %>%
  filter(!grepl("^\\d+$", token)) %>%
  count(token, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(20, n) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, fct_reorder(token, n))) +
  geom_col()

Now that stop words are removed, we can see that the top words include “patient”, “left”, “procedure”, “pain”, and others. A lot of the words in the top 20 are related to surgical procedures such as “anesthesia” and “incision”. This is expected because the most entries are from the surgery specialty. These words give us context about the procedure being done on the patient.

Question 4

mtsamples2 %>%
  unnest_ngrams(ngram, transcription, n = 2) %>%
  count(ngram, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(20, n) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, fct_reorder(ngram, n))) +
  geom_col()

mtsamples2 %>%
  unnest_ngrams(ngram, transcription, n = 3) %>%
  count(ngram, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(20, n) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, fct_reorder(ngram, n))) +
  geom_col()

In both ngrams, the top most frequent phrase includes “the patient”. A lot of the phrases also describe the location of something. The tri-grams give more context which makes sense since it includes an addition word in the phrase.

Question 5

library(tidyr)

#words before
mtsamples2 %>%
  unnest_ngrams(ngram, transcription, n = 2) %>%
  separate(ngram, into = c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ") %>%
  select(word1, word2) %>%
  filter(word2 == "medical") %>%
  count(word1, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(20, n) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, fct_reorder(word1, n))) +
  geom_col()

#words after
mtsamples2 %>%
  unnest_ngrams(ngram, transcription, n = 2) %>%
  separate(ngram, into = c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ") %>%
  select(word1, word2) %>%
  filter(word1 == "medical") %>%
  count(word2, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(20, n) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, fct_reorder(word2, n))) +
  geom_col()

The word I chose was “medical”. The most frequent words to come before “medical” are “past”, “the”, and “to”. The most frequent words to come after “medical” are “history”, “center”, and “problems”.

top5 <- mtsamples2 %>%
  group_by(medical_specialty) %>%
  unnest_tokens(token, transcription) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = c("token" = "word")) %>%
  filter(!grepl("^\\d+$", token)) %>%
  count(token, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(5, n)
